As pere· grini they bad the usual rights over their reedmen, with which the father could not interfere, but on coming under the - patria potestas, the son would naturally lose not only his right of testamentary disposition and owning property, but also his rights over his freedmen. These consisted (1) in the general obsequium, reverentia, or honour, which the freedman had to render to his patron, Cic. ad.
